metadata.name: Refractions #1
metadata.description:
Refractions is a study of frequencies, harmonies and abstract representations of natural phenomena. 

It is an experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.


Probabilities;

- 14 compositions with variations.

- 2 background color.

- 19 different base color palette (2 monochrome).

- 2 distinct textures with variations.

-  2 different alpha types; tangential & sinusoidal.

- Different edges.

- Several starting positions and styles (wavy or straight).


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, April 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Theatergoers #249
metadata.description:
Simple black and white blobs align to create delicate stories of an audience at their local theater. Follow their eyes in each piece to get started, but don't stare for too long——that's rude.

- press 's' to save the image at its current resolution
- press 'h' to say hello

metadata.name: 56 Modes #227
metadata.description:
A hybrid of Conway's Game of Life and Wolfram's cellular automata, and a continuation of my genesis piece. Each begins with two of 56 possible modes, and evolves further using a set of 512 modes. The animation runs until all cells die, then loops continuously from the start.

Press spacebar to pause, and s to save a .png of the canvas.

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #86
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It’s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you’re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic “Hashed/Hatched” aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: Outside your Window #55
metadata.description:
Never take for granted that we sit in the safety of our homes, behind our windows, sheltered from the elements outside. 

The characteristics of the rain outside the window, and the window itself, will be determined by the mint hash. However, the background color of this piece will constantly change based on the hour of day it is loaded, hence note that the thumbnail will only technically be accurate 1/24 hours out of the day as it represents a static snapshot taken at the time of token rendering.

100% of the primary proceeds will be donated towards flood relief efforts for the devastating December 2021 floods in Malaysia.

Made in p5js
Created December 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Organicon, variation I #374
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
A unique generator creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation I is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. Warning: the preview thumbnail is a pale shadow of live view.

Interface: a first mouse click clears the screen, creates an new iteration and enables active mode. In active mode each iteration remains on screen for a limited amount of time before being replaced by the next. A second mouse click disables active mode. In active mode a small dot is displayed in the lower right corner. '+' and '-' zoom in and out.

metadata.name: On the sea, I ... #219
metadata.description:
Generative painting based on churning waves with floating buoys. Represented in three different media.

Features:
- Three drawing styles: "watercolor" 70%, "brush" 30%, or "block" 70%
- Warm white or blue waves
- Variable border and column sizes
- Number of columns
- Calm waves at the edges or center
- Color 80% or red 20% buoys
- Buoy drawing style, "watercolor" or "brush"

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

metadata.name: Omega Point #100
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Hapna 'v2' #84
metadata.description:
A generative series of textural compositions.

Hapna ‘v2’ is a further experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.

Observe how Hapna ‘v2’ blends and creates its textures in time.

Probabilities;

- 8 compositions with variations - 1 composition is rare.

- 3 base color area - 2 monochrome palette.

- 4 different middle shapes - ‘No Middle Shape’ is very rare.

- 6 different color placements.


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, February 2022
@distcollective
